* Metronic 9 Tailwind

Architecture

* Clean Architecture
* CQRS
* Modular Monolith
* Domain Driven Design
* Event Driven Ready

---

## GENERAL RULES

Always follow:

* DDL.md
* ARCHITECTURE.md

Never invent:

* Tables
* Columns
* Foreign Keys
* Relationships

Use only structures defined in DDL.md.

If a required structure is missing:

* Stop
* Explain what is missing
* Wait for user decision

Do not create alternative schemas.

Do not implement any table, service, or business rule for a future
OrganizationGroup tier — it does not exist in DDL.md yet. However,
new code must not assume Corporation is the system's absolute and
permanent top level (e.g. avoid hardcoded "Corporation has no
parent" logic baked deep into business rules). OrganizationGroup
will be added via migration when a real business need arises.

Do not implement ABAC/Care-Team authorization logic now — no table,
service, or business rule for it exists in DDL.md yet. RBAC is the
current and only authorization model. However, new code must not
assume role-based checks are the permanent, only mechanism for
clinical-data access (student records, assessments, case notes,
reports) — ABAC/Care-Team may be introduced later for these.

Do not implement tenant subscription, feature licensing, or usage
metering tables/logic now — none exist in DDL.md yet. However, new
code must not hardcode the assumption that every tenant has
unlimited access to every module; `menu_item.feature_flag` already
exists as the seam this will eventually plug into.

---

## DATABASE RULES

All entities must:

* Inherit BaseEntity
* Support Audit Fields
* Support Soft Delete where applicable

Required audit fields:

* CreatedAt
* CreatedBy
* UpdatedAt
* UpdatedBy
* DeletedAt
* DeletedBy
* IsDeleted

Use EF Core Fluent Configuration.

Do not use DataAnnotations for database design.

---

## MULTI TENANT RULES

All business data must be tenant-aware.

Corporation boundaries must always be respected.

Branch boundaries must always be respected.

No cross-corporation data leakage is allowed.

Queries must always respect tenant context.

---

## CONFIGURABLE REFERENCE DATA RULES

Business classifications must never be hardcoded.

Use configurable reference data for:

* Session Types
* Therapy Types
* Program Types
* Assessment Types
* Goal Categories
* Development Areas
* Educator Types
* Meeting Types
* Leave Types
* Attendance Reasons
* Lead Sources
* Lead Statuses
* Payment Methods
* Discount Types
* Contract Types
* Consent Types
* KPI Categories
* Notification Types
* Student Statuses
* Enrollment Statuses

If a classification may change in the future:

Use reference data.

Do not use enums.

---

## REFERENCE DATA SAFETY

Reference data values must never be physically deleted.

If business records already reference a value:

* Prevent deletion
* Allow deactivation only

Historical records must remain valid.

---

## LOCALIZATION RULES

All user-facing content must support localization.

Do not hardcode display text.

Support:

* Turkish
* Future additional languages

Menus, notifications, templates and reference data must be translatable.

Use translation infrastructure defined in the architecture.

---

## AUTHORIZATION RULES

Never authorize by role name directly.

Use permission-based authorization.

Roles are configurable.

Permissions are the source of truth.

Support:

* Dynamic Roles
* Dynamic Permissions
* Tenant-specific Roles

---

## API RULES

Controllers must remain thin.

No business logic inside controllers.

Use:

* MediatR
* CQRS
* FluentValidation

All responses must use:

ApiResponse<T>

Support:

* Pagination
* Filtering
* Sorting

Global exception middleware must be used.

---

## APPLICATION LAYER RULES

Business logic belongs in:

* Commands
* Command Handlers
* Domain Services

Queries must never modify data.

Commands must never return large datasets.

---

## DOMAIN RULES

Domain entities must remain persistence-ignorant.

Protect invariants inside domain entities.

Avoid anemic domain models.

Use Value Objects where appropriate.

---

## EVENT RULES

Prefer Domain Events when:

* Student Enrolled
* Assessment Completed
* Session Completed
* Package Purchased
* Contract Signed
* Leave Approved

Avoid direct coupling between modules.

Future distributed events must be possible.

---

## WORKFLOW RULES

Workflow transitions must be validated.

Invalid transitions must be rejected.

Examples:

Completed -> Draft
Rejected

Cancelled -> Approved
Rejected

Rules must be enforced consistently.

---

## FILE MANAGEMENT RULES

Use file metadata records.

Never store business files directly in entities.

Use file references.

Support:

* Local Storage
* Future S3 Storage

File access must be permission controlled.

---

## FINANCIAL DATA RULES

Financial records are immutable.

Never physically delete:

* Payments
* Invoices
* Credit Usage History
* Refund History

Corrections must use:

* Reversal Records
* Adjustment Records

Audit history must remain intact.

---

## CONTRACT & CONSENT RULES

Signed documents are immutable.

Contract history must be preserved.

Consent history must be preserved.

Never overwrite accepted consent records.

Version history is mandatory.

---

## AUDIT RULES

All critical business actions must be auditable.

Examples:

* Student Created
* Student Updated
* Assessment Completed
* Session Completed
* Package Purchased
* Contract Signed
* Leave Approved

Audit history must never be deleted.

---

## SECURITY RULES

Follow OWASP recommendations.

Never expose:

* Internal IDs unnecessarily
* Sensitive medical information
* Financial information
* Tenant data belonging to another corporation

Validate all inputs.

Use least privilege principle.

---

## PERFORMANCE RULES

Avoid N+1 queries.

Use projections for list screens.

Use caching for:

* Permissions
* Menus
* Settings
* Reference Data
* Translations

Design for future scalability.

---

## OUTPUT RULES

Generate code incrementally.

After each major layer:

* Stop
* Explain generated files
* Wait for confirmation

Do not generate multiple business modules at once.

Generate only the requested module.
